==English==

===Etymology===
Middle English and Middle French ''[[sillabe]]'', from {{etyl|la}} {{term|syllaba|lang=la}}, from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|συλλαβή||sc=polytonic|tr=sullabē|lang=grc}}, from {{term|συλλαμβάνω||I gather together|sc=polytonic|tr=sullambanō|lang=grc}}, from {{term|συν|συν-|together|sc=polytonic|tr=sun-|lang=grc}} + {{term|λαμβάνω||I take|tr=lambanō|lang=grc|sc=polytonic}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP|US}} {{IPA|/ˈsɪləbɫ/}}
* {{audio|en-uk-syllable.ogg|Audio (UK)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{linguistics}} A unit of human speech that is interpreted by the listener as a single sound, although syllables usually consist of one or more [[vowel]] sounds, either alone or combined with the sound of one or more [[consonant]]s; a word consists of one or more syllables.
# The written representation of a given pronounced syllable.

